<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM PROTEST</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul 31 12:00:35 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Protesting takes so many forms. In my case, I was a gung ho sob when in college, ROTC was required by law at the land grant college, attend or get a failing grade, and then you had to take it over anyway. We all went for the 2 years required, the last 2 years were an option, and if you took it, you graduated with second louie bars...then off to nam. This was  62 to 65.<br><br>
Later, I was afraid the draft was at my front door (they were) and I joined a NG unit to beat it. I wanted to be an officer like my father (Air Force retired) but I'd heard the stories from Benning and thought I had a way to sneak into the war as an officer. I attended the NG  OCS program for a little over a year after AIT (11B10) and did well. The plan was to get the commission in the guard, then go RA. ( I know, don't ask). I took my basic at Ft. Jackson on emergency WWII cement slabs with squad tents. Cold coal fired showers for 11 weeks. (NOTE: in 65 they were drafting 45,000  19 yr olds a month.<br><br>
About this time one of my best friends sat me down and gave me a bit of a political look at what was going on in the war, and I saw that this was not the war I wanted to be in after all. To late.<br><br>
About two years in the NG was enough, so I simply quit going to meetings, and was drafted. I already had basic, and AIT, and was ripe for the field in 1967 when the FBI finally cought up with me. The FBI asked me if I was going to submit to induction, or be led away in handcuffs, next stupid question.<br><br>
However..I got on the phone and was offered a job in Winnipeg, Canada and was going to run, when the FBI found out and arrested me. I was in jail for 37 1/2 days..charged with refusing induction. My dad bailed me outa jail, and I submitted to induction, and was shipped to Ft. Lewis, and was sitting in a barracks waiting for the next plane overseas. There was a string of events that led me to hitch hike to Vancouver, and I stayed in Canada for 7 years, returning to the US in 74 under the Clemency discharge program. Two year earned re-entry program, another complete story by itself.<br><br>
For 7 years there was an FBI warrant for my arrest for: International flight to avoid prosecution, desertion, and subversive activities. When the young new RCMP kid was at my door asking if I was going to stay, (I was a landed immigrant, and was going nowhere), he produced the FBI wanted poster with my name and pictures. He only had 1 copy, wouldn't give it up for my wall.<br><br>
Film at 11. I'd write more, but this seems like a lot right now.
